19: Makes ANSI escape character sequences for producing colored terminal
20: text and cursor positioning work under MS Windows.
21: ANSI escape character sequences have long been used to produce colored
22: terminal text and cursor positioning on Unix and Macs. Colorama makes this
23: work on Windows, too, by wrapping stdout, stripping ANSI sequences it finds
24: (which otherwise show up as gobbledygook in your output), and converting
25: them into the appropriate win32 calls to modify the state of the terminal.
26: On other platforms, Colorama does nothing.
28: Colorama also provides some shortcuts to help generate ANSI sequences but
29: works fine in conjunction with any other ANSI sequence generation library,
32: This has the upshot of providing a simple cross-platform API for printing
33: colored terminal text from Python, and has the happy side-effect that
34: existing applications or libraries which use ANSI sequences to produce
35: colored output on Linux or Macs can now also work on Windows, simply by
38: An alternative approach is to install 'ansi.sys' on Windows machines,
39: which provides the same behaviour for all applications running in
40: terminals. Colorama is intended for situations where that isn't easy
41: (e.g. maybe your app doesn't have an installer.)
43: Demo scripts in the source code repository prints some colored text
44: using ANSI sequences. Compare their output under Gnome-terminal's
45: built in ANSI handling, versus on Windows Command-Prompt using
